ionalism were crafted, that were claimed to be immune to the earlier criticisms. This volume contains 12 papers in which various aspects of this dialectic are covered. A number of papers continue the trend to defend foundationalism, and foundationalism's commitment to basic beliefs and basic knowledge, against various attacks. Others aim to show that one important objection against coherentism, viz. that the notion of 'coherence' is too vague to be useful, can be countered.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aFoundationalism (Theory of knowledge)vCongresses. 4aErkenntnistheorie. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aDouven, Igor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEng, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHale, Bob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHales, Steven D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamilton, Andy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Christian B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNanay, Bence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPritchard, Duncan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoeser, Sabine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoeser, Sabine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRood, Ron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRood, Ron, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWeidemann, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWoudenberg, René van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWoudenberg, René, eeditor.4edt4htt